Fish Outside a Box

Silver scales catch morning light,
No longer trapped in cardboard walls,
The fish breathes deep the open air—
Though air is not what calls.

Once confined by rigid edges,
Corners sharp and space so small,
Now the world spreads wide before her,
Ocean vast beyond them all.

Gasping in this strange new freedom,
Fins that flutter, seeking stream,
She discovers that escape
Is harder than it seemed.

The box was safe, predictable,
Its boundaries well-defined,
But out here in the boundless space
She's lost what peace she'd find.

Yet something in her spirit stirs,
A wildness long suppressed,
The fish outside the box now knows
That freedom is her quest.

Though the journey may be treacherous,
And the path unclear ahead,
She'd rather die pursuing dreams
Than live safely instead.

So swim, dear fish, through morning mist,
Let courage be your guide,
For those who dare to leave their box
Find oceans deep and wide.

The box sits empty, corners cold,
A monument to fear,
While somewhere in the endless blue,
A fish swims crystal clear.